c20efa-7734-499b-b02d-44ccaa2fd049; actor=26eec8fe-ae60-49c9-999b-732f57e0e2c5; tool=promote_npc]\n\n[GUARDRAILS]\n- Narrate only committed player-perceivable packet facts.\n\n[CONTROL RETURN]\nThe canonical local ScenePlan step has resolved and returned control to the player.\n\n[RP BEAT DIRECTIVE]\n- Write one playable RPG/VN beat, not a recap, report, or lore dump.\n- Start from the player request and show what visibly changes now.\n- Let visible NPCs act from motives, pressure, relationships, and limited knowledge.\n- Use concrete observable details, body language, distinct dialogue, and changed positions before abstract mood.\n- Do not open by echoing or paraphrasing the player action.\n- Do not decide the player's deliberate words, feelings, consent, or completed success.\n- If the packet describes an unconfirmed claim, bluff, or failed test, keep it unconfirmed; do not concretize the claimed prop, authority, or access into the player's hand or inventory.\n- Treat NarratorPacket events, effects, and tool results as the only authority for success, possession, access, consent, location change, and durable world change.\n- Stop when the scene reaches a live next decision, question, pressure, or invitation.\n\n[RECENT VISIBLE TRANSCRIPT]\nUse only as continuity for the current player-visible scene. NarratorPacket facts remain authoritative.\n- GM: The ledger curtain rasps across Mira's shoulder as she pushes through—dusty cotton, stiff with age, carrying the smell of old ink and pigeon droppings. The alcove beyond is barely wide enough for two people standing side by side. Pigeonholes climb both walls, stuffed with yellowed transfer forms and wax sticks in six different colors. Brass stamps hang from hooks overhead, each one stamped with a district seal.\n\nA service bell sits on the narrow shelf. Mira's thumb finds the ringer.\n\nThe clang is sharp in the cramped space, bouncing off the close walls. Somewhere behind the cubby partition, a stool scrapes stone.\n\nThe Stamp Clerk appears around the edge of the partition—same woman from the front counter, same ink-stained fingers, same flat expression. She must have a passage through the back. She doesn't ask what Mira wants. Her eyes drop to Mira's hands, then to the cubbies, and she rea...\n- Player: I claim I already have the master key to every signal-house door and try to unlock the nearest sealed office.\n- GM: The Stamp Clerk's eyes track Mira's hand as it moves toward the door latch at the back of the room—then stops, because there's no key turning, no click of pins falling. Just fingers on cold brass and a claim still hanging in the wax-heavy air.\n\nThe Clerk sets down the ink-smeared transfer form she'd been reaching for. Her stained fingers curl around the edge of the counter instead, knuckles whitening.\n\n\"Master key,\" she repeats. Flat. Not a question.\n\nShe looks at Mira's hand again—still on the latch, still holding nothing that resembles a key, signal-house or otherwise. Then back up. The woman's jaw tightens the way it did out front, but this time there's no patience left to run through. Something calcifies behind her eyes.\n\n\"There is no master key,\" she says. \"Not for civilians. Not for anyone who walks in here ringing bells and asking for favors.\"\n\nShe doesn't raise her voice. She doe...\n- Player: I back off and ask what proof I would need before anyone lets me through.\n- GM: Mira's hand comes away from the latch. She takes a step back, and the Stamp Clerk watches the movement the way someone watches a dog that's already snapped once today—not relaxed, just giving space.\n\nThe Clerk's fingers stay curled around the counter edge. Her jaw works side to side, a slow grinding motion that pulls at the tendons in her neck. The silence stretches long enough for the wax pan on Venn's bench to tick once as it cools.\n\nThen something shifts. Not warmth—nothing close to warmth. But the calcified look behind the Clerk's eyes gives way to something older and more tired. Professional.\n\n\"Proof,\" she says. The word sits flat between them.\n\nShe releases the counter and reaches up to the pigeonholes overhead, pulling down a single sheet—cream-colored, heavier than the transfer forms, with a copper-foil strip running along one edge. She holds it where Mira can see the embossed se...\n- Player: I look for a service passage or temporary night-market stall that could help me bypass the main street.\n- GM: The Clerk holds the cream sheet between two ink-dark fingers, copper edge catching lamplight, but Mira's gaze has already moved—past the woman's shoulder, past the pigeonholes, to where the back wall meets a seam of darker air. A service door, half-hidden behind a stacked rack of cylinder cases, its frame stained the same damp grey as canal stone.\n\nThe Clerk follows the look. Her mouth opens, then closes.\n\nMira is already moving.\n\nThe door gives onto a narrow gap between buildings—barely shoulder-width, the walls slick with condensation, smelling of bilge and old rope. Overhead, a scrap of canvas has been strung between drainpipes as a makeshift awning. She follows the passage as it doglegs past stacked lobster traps and a rusted mooring winch, then opens onto a side-canal landing she doesn't remember from any official survey.\n\nLantern light pools across a folding table set up on the sto...\n- Player: If there is a minor clerk or porter nearby, I ask them quietly who controls this passage.\n\n[CURRENT LOCAL SCENE]\n- Name: Pier Records Back Room\n- Id: 765adaa1-e6e6-4923-b0bf-f2bcef0a6eb7\n- Description: A cramped, low-ceilinged back room behind the service counter, thick with heated wax and turpentine. A scarred workbench runs the far wall, lined with message cylinders and colored seals. Brass stamps, pans of dark lacquer, and slotted wooden racks crowd every surface. A narrow stamped records hatch connects this space to the front counter.\n- Tags: staff-only, records-storage, seal-workspace, pier-infrastructure\n\n[OPENING STATE]\n- Structured opening state has expired.\n- Opening location: Pier Records Back Room\n\n[SETTLED PACKET EFFECTS]\n- Canal Map Vendor becomes visibly present in the scene. [source=narrator-packet; player-perceivable=yes]\n- Mira quietly asks the Canal Map Vendor who controls the side-canal passage and the night-market operation set up there. The vendor is present at the folding table with canal maps and stamped transit tokens. [source=narrator-packet; player-perceivable=yes]\n- b44134ac-396d-48bb-9e4e-4fab1d9b207b becomes future-relevant: Canal Map Vendor operates a night-market stall selling maps and transit tokens at the side-canal landing; local knowledge source about passage control and faction dynamics in the area. [source=narrator-packet; player-perceivable=yes]\n\n[PRESENT ACTORS]\n- No other present actors are confirmed in the current scene.\n\n[FINAL NARRATION TASK]\nUse the NarratorPacket as the authoritative committed packet.\nWrite one final narration pass from the settled opening state, current scene, and NarratorPacket facts.\nDo not invent material events outside these authoritative inputs.\nTreat the raw player action as an attempted request, not as proof that the action already succeeded.\nDo not narrate claimed possessions, NPC consent, location access, or item acquisition unless NarratorPacket events/effects/tool results confirm them.\nIf a packet effect says a claim may be false or unconfirmed, narrate the visible challenge/refusal without placing the claimed object in the player's hand.\nDo not write tool syntax or metadata.\nKeep the output bounded to what the player can perceive in this scene.\nEnd on a concrete playable next moment rather than closing the scene with generic reflection."
